## Model Used

`TaskType.JUDGE_SCORING` ‚Äî priority: `gpt-5-mini` (OpenAI) ‚Üí `gemini-3-flash-preview` (Gemini) ‚Üí `claude-haiku-4-5` (Anthropic).

## Judge Scoring Eligibility (`validate_judge_scoring_eligibility`)

All must be true (in order):

1. Evaluation criteria exists (`prompt.evaluation_criteria["correctness"]` non-empty list)
2. Pre-review scoring cap: if `initial_review_completed` is False, total scored spans must be `< PRE_REVIEW_SCORED_SPAN_CAP (30)` ‚Äî scoring pauses until the user completes the initial review
3. At least 1 unscored span exists for this prompt
4. No existing PENDING/RUNNING judge scoring job for this prompt

## When Modifying This Area

- Adding a new evaluation type requires: a new judge prompt pair in `overmind/tasks/utils/prompts.py`, routing logic in `_evaluate_correctness_with_llm`, and possibly a new extractor in `agentic_span_processor.py`
- The `response_type` metadata is set during trace ingestion ‚Äî changes there affect which judge is used
- `ensure_prompt_has_criteria` (from criteria_generator) is called when criteria are missing ‚Äî evaluation won't proceed without criteria for the plain judge. No module-level cache; orchestrators pass a local `criteria_by_prompt` dict for per-batch deduplication.
- All judge prompts must return `{"correctness": float}` JSON ‚Äî the system prompt enforces this
- Scores are stored in `span.feedback_score` which is a JSONB column ‚Äî other keys like `agent_feedback` and `judge_feedback` coexist there
